content.description: Very Good route that is consistent movement at the grade and well worth the visit.  The only crux would be the funky start (1st move) and then just the steep jugs all the way to the top, don't flame out to soon!
content.protection: Well protected sport route with 5 Bolts to fixed anchors up top for rappel.
content.location: This is the first route just right of the dirty chimney splitting the cliffs.  Steep route up jugs and large pockets.  Rappel off and enjoy the FUN!

content.description:
Starts on very porous rock. Climb up steep rock on deep pockets, including a mono, to a big move onto the face. keep it together while making the awkward transition onto the face.  

  This is a fun and relatively sustained route.  bring your tendon strength.
content.location: one route to the right of 'bored of inquiry'.

content.description:
Climb up the right side of the chimney on the outside of the blunt arete.  Getting off the ground and established is quite tricky.  After a few moves some better holds are encountered.  After this a horizontal break is encountered allowing a nice rest, before the easier finish. 

  Probably a bit soft for the 12a grade, considered 11a if the backwall is used.
content.location: Far left side of Swiss Wall.  Up the hill and left from White Gang Wall.  To the right is an unknown 5.8 jug haul.

content.description:
Thin in a couple of places -

 Established by P. Zurcher and L. Reinmuth 5/12
content.location: Swiss Wall.  Go past Bored of Inquiry and around the corner.  There is an alcove.  On the right are (2) 10s and then this is on the darker rock on the left of the big off-width crack.   Rap off the quick links

content.description: Boulder problem start to a rest followed by consistent steep climbing.
content.location: right and around the corner from the brie and bleu corridor routes.

content.description: Steep route for the grade on huge jugs with a slightly awkward start.  Good route but very short and the warm up for the Swiss Cheese Wall.
content.protection: 4 Bolts to fixed anchors and pretty darn protected I would say!
content.location: This is the first route just 5 feet left of a dirty chimney splitting the Swiss Cheese Wall area.  Rappel down but this would be the good warm up for the routes on the main Swiss Cheese wall just right.

content.description: The best route on the wall with excellent protection and fluid movements.  The crux is down low during the first two bolts then it's pretty much a cruiser.  Not to be missed if going to Jacks Canyon!!
content.protection: Six conveniently placed bolts will get you to the fixed anchors up top for your rappel.
content.location: This is the second route right of the dirty chimney splitting the walls.  The first two bolts go straight up; then follow two right-angling bolts; then straight up the well-spaced but easy climbing sport route to the fixed anchors.  ***Please take note that there is a lone bolt about 15-20 feet up the wall in between this route and the 5.9 to the left of it.  This is an unfinished route that leads to nowhere; make sure you traverse right when doing this climb!!  Have Fun

content.description:
While this route has a few good moves, the bottom of the route is almost entirely manufactured. 

  Start on  some drilled pockets and head up past some smaller drilled pockets to the small roof.  Set up for the roof on drilled jugs and make one hard pull to the first natural hold on the route.  Once established over the roof the difficulty eases and it is a fun romp to the top. 

  Usually referred to as 12a but I thought it was easier.
content.location: On the Far right side of Lower Swiss Wall sometimes referred to as White Gang Wall.  This is the rightmost route on the wall with the huge roof above.

content.description: Middle route on the left wall, with funky bolting.  Starts at a hangerless bolt.  Sustained and pleasant climbing.  Third bolt is a perma-spinner.
content.protection: Two open shuts and a third closed shut.
content.location: First route right of Swiss Miss

content.description: A decent route located in a little alcove. Not bad 5.9 climbing. Could increase in stars with traffic. Very dusty route. Maybe not a "destination climb" at Jack's but if you're just looking for vertical feet then this'll do.
content.location: Route is located 50 feet past Fe Fi Fo Fun in an alcove on two facing reddish walls.

content.description: Climb up the overhanging arete on pockets to a large square block. Pull over the block to horizontal crack.
content.protection: Six bolts to open shuts anchors.
content.location: Route is located on the arete at the bottom of the hill.

content.description:
As with the other climb in this alcove it is dusty and does not appear to be heavily trafficed. Still fun 5.9 climbing but could increase with traffic.  

  Last few moves are odd as there are anchors 8feet below and 4 feet right of the route's anchors. A possible top rope only route?
content.location: The route is located 50 feet past Fe Fi Fo Fun and on the opposite facing wall as Brie in an alcove with two facing reddish walls

content.description:
Excellent climbing in Jacks Canyon and an excellent option on hot summer days: The combination of a northern orientation and a dense stand of trees make the crag far more comfortable when Casino or Cracker Jack are blazing infernos.  While the number of routes is limited, there are is great rock and fun routes at a range of grades.

Approaching the anchors on Yarlsberg
